    {
      "kind": "content",
      "content": [
        {
          "anchor": "overview",
          "level": 2,
          "text": "Overview",
          "type": "heading"
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": "When you create shadows, the system draws them in the default user coordinate space, where  coordinates are independent from the pixel values of any particular device. Rotations, translations, and other transformations of the current transformation matrix (CTM) donâ€™t affect the shadow or the apparent position of the shadowâ€™s light source."
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": "A shadow has two positional parameters: an x-offset and a y-offset. Express these values with a single size data type ("
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": true,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/coregraphics/cgsize"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": " in iOS, "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": true,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/foundation/nssize"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": " in macOS), using the units of the default user coordinate space. Positive values for these offsets extend down and to the right from the userâ€™s perspective."
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": "In addition to its positional parameters, a shadow also contains a blur radius, which specifies how much the system blurs a drawn objectâ€™s image mask before compositing the image onto the destination. A value of "
            },
            {
              "type": "codeVoice",
              "code": "0"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": " produces no blur. Larger values produce an increasingly large blurred shadow. "
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": "You can use an "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": false,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/uikit/nsshadow"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": " object in one of two ways. First, you can set it, like a color or a font, where "
            },
            {
              "type": "codeVoice",
              "code": "NSShadow"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": " attributes apply to everything you draw until you apply another shadow or restore a previous graphics state. Second, you can use an "
            },
            {
              "type": "codeVoice",
              "code": "NSShadow"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": " instance as the value for the "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": true,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/uikit/nsshadowattributename"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": " text attribute, so the system applies the shadow to the glyphs corresponding to the characters bearing this attribute."
            }
          ]
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
